properties.name: fhirObservation
properties.documentation: Measurements and simple assertions made about a patient, device or other subject.

properties.name: resourceType
properties.documentation: This is a Observation resource

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: The logical id of the resource, as used in the URL for the resource. Once assigned, this value never changes.

properties.name: meta
properties.documentation: The metadata about the resource. This is content that is maintained by the infrastructure. Changes to the content might not always be associated with version changes to the resource.

properties.name: implicitRules
properties.documentation: A reference to a set of rules that were followed when the resource was constructed, and which must be understood when processing the content. Often, this is a reference to an implementation guide that defines the special rules along with other profiles etc.

properties.name: language
properties.documentation: The base language in which the resource is written.

properties.name: text
properties.documentation: A human-readable narrative that contains a summary of the resource and can be used to represent the content of the resource to a human. The narrative need not encode all the structured data, but is required to contain sufficient detail to make it "clinically safe" for a human to just read the narrative. Resource definitions may define what content should be represented in the narrative to ensure clinical safety.

properties.name: contained
properties.documentation: These resources do not have an independent existence apart from the resource that contains them - they cannot be identified independently, and nor can they have their own independent transaction scope.

properties.name: identifier
properties.documentation: A unique identifier assigned to this observation.

properties.name: basedOn
properties.documentation: A plan, proposal or order that is fulfilled in whole or in part by this event.  For example, a MedicationRequest may require a patient to have laboratory test performed before  it is dispensed.

properties.name: partOf
properties.documentation: A larger event of which this particular Observation is a component or step.  For example,  an observation as part of a procedure.

properties.name: status
properties.documentation: The status of the result value.

properties.name: category
properties.documentation: A code that classifies the general type of observation being made.

properties.name: code
properties.documentation: Describes what was observed. Sometimes this is called the observation "name".

properties.name: subject
properties.documentation: The patient, or group of patients, location, or device this observation is about and into whose record the observation is placed. If the actual focus of the observation is different from the subject (or a sample of, part, or region of the subject), the `focus` element or the `code` itself specifies the actual focus of the observation.

properties.name: focus
properties.documentation: The actual focus of an observation when it is not the patient of record representing something or someone associated with the patient such as a spouse, parent, fetus, or donor. For example, fetus observations in a mother's record.  The focus of an observation could also be an existing condition,  an intervention, the subject's diet,  another observation of the subject,  or a body structure such as tumor or implanted device.   An example use case would be using the Observation resource to capture whether the mother is trained to change her child's tracheostomy tube. In this example, the child is the patient of record and the mother is the focus.

properties.name: encounter
properties.documentation: The healthcare event  (e.g. a patient and healthcare provider interaction) during which this observation is made.

properties.name: effectiveDateTime
properties.documentation: The time or time-period the observed value is asserted as being true. For biological subjects - e.g. human patients - this is usually called the "physiologically relevant time". This is usually either the time of the procedure or of specimen collection, but very often the source of the date/time is not known, only the date/time itself.

properties.name: effectivePeriod
properties.documentation: The time or time-period the observed value is asserted as being true. For biological subjects - e.g. human patients - this is usually called the "physiologically relevant time". This is usually either the time of the procedure or of specimen collection, but very often the source of the date/time is not known, only the date/time itself.

properties.name: effectiveTiming
properties.documentation: The time or time-period the observed value is asserted as being true. For biological subjects - e.g. human patients - this is usually called the "physiologically relevant time". This is usually either the time of the procedure or of specimen collection, but very often the source of the date/time is not known, only the date/time itself.

properties.name: effectiveInstant
properties.documentation: The time or time-period the observed value is asserted as being true. For biological subjects - e.g. human patients - this is usually called the "physiologically relevant time". This is usually either the time of the procedure or of specimen collection, but very often the source of the date/time is not known, only the date/time itself.

properties.name: issued
properties.documentation: The date and time this version of the observation was made available to providers, typically after the results have been reviewed and verified.

properties.name: performer
properties.documentation: Who was responsible for asserting the observed value as "true".

properties.name: valueQuantity
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: valueCodeableConcept
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: valueString
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: valueBoolean
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: valueInteger
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: valueRange
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: valueRatio
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: valueSampledData
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: valueTime
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: valueDateTime
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: valuePeriod
properties.documentation: The information determined as a result of making the observation, if the information has a simple value.

properties.name: dataAbsentReason
properties.documentation: Provides a reason why the expected value in the element Observation.value[x] is missing.

properties.name: interpretation
properties.documentation: A categorical assessment of an observation value.  For example, high, low, normal.

properties.name: note
properties.documentation: Comments about the observation or the results.

properties.name: bodySite
properties.documentation: Indicates the site on the subject's body where the observation was made (i.e. the target site).

properties.name: method
properties.documentation: Indicates the mechanism used to perform the observation.

properties.name: specimen
properties.documentation: The specimen that was used when this observation was made.

properties.name: device
properties.documentation: The device used to generate the observation data.

properties.name: referenceRange
properties.documentation: Guidance on how to interpret the value by comparison to a normal or recommended range.  Multiple reference ranges are interpreted as an "OR".   In other words, to represent two distinct target populations, two `referenceRange` elements would be used.

properties.name: hasMember
properties.documentation: This observation is a group observation (e.g. a battery, a panel of tests, a set of vital sign measurements) that includes the target as a member of the group.

properties.name: derivedFrom
properties.documentation: The target resource that represents a measurement from which this observation value is derived. For example, a calculated anion gap or a fetal measurement based on an ultrasound image.

properties.name: component
properties.documentation: Some observations have multiple component observations.  These component observations are expressed as separate code value pairs that share the same attributes.  Examples include systolic and diastolic component observations for blood pressure measurement and multiple component observations for genetics observations.

properties.name: fhirMeta
properties.documentation: The metadata about a resource. This is content in the resource that is maintained by the infrastructure. Changes to the content might not always be associated with version changes to the resource.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: versionId
properties.documentation: The version specific identifier, as it appears in the version portion of the URL. This value changes when the resource is created, updated, or deleted.

properties.name: lastUpdated
properties.documentation: When the resource last changed - e.g. when the version changed.

properties.name: source
properties.documentation: A uri that identifies the source system of the resource. This provides a minimal amount of [[[Provenance]]] information that can be used to track or differentiate the source of information in the resource. The source may identify another FHIR server, document, message, database, etc.

properties.name: profile
properties.documentation: A list of profiles (references to [[[StructureDefinition]]] resources) that this resource claims to conform to. The URL is a reference to [[[StructureDefinition.url]]].

properties.name: security
properties.documentation: Security labels applied to this resource. These tags connect specific resources to the overall security policy and infrastructure.

properties.name: tag
properties.documentation: Tags applied to this resource. Tags are intended to be used to identify and relate resources to process and workflow, and applications are not required to consider the tags when interpreting the meaning of a resource.

properties.name: fhirCoding
properties.documentation: A reference to a code defined by a terminology system.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: system
properties.documentation: The identification of the code system that defines the meaning of the symbol in the code.

properties.name: version
properties.documentation: The version of the code system which was used when choosing this code. Note that a well-maintained code system does not need the version reported, because the meaning of codes is consistent across versions. However this cannot consistently be assured, and when the meaning is not guaranteed to be consistent, the version SHOULD be exchanged.

properties.name: code
properties.documentation: A symbol in syntax defined by the system. The symbol may be a predefined code or an expression in a syntax defined by the coding system (e.g. post-coordination).

properties.name: display
properties.documentation: A representation of the meaning of the code in the system, following the rules of the system.

properties.name: userSelected
properties.documentation: Indicates that this coding was chosen by a user directly - e.g. off a pick list of available items (codes or displays).

properties.name: fhirNarrative
properties.documentation: A human-readable summary of the resource conveying the essential clinical and business information for the resource.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: status
properties.documentation: The status of the narrative - whether it's entirely generated (from just the defined data or the extensions too), or whether a human authored it and it may contain additional data.

properties.name: div
properties.documentation: The actual narrative content, a stripped down version of XHTML.

properties.name: fhirIdentifier
properties.documentation: An identifier - identifies some entity uniquely and unambiguously. Typically this is used for business identifiers.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: use
properties.documentation: The purpose of this identifier.

properties.name: type
properties.documentation: A coded type for the identifier that can be used to determine which identifier to use for a specific purpose.

properties.name: system
properties.documentation: Establishes the namespace for the value - that is, a URL that describes a set values that are unique.

properties.name: value
properties.documentation: The portion of the identifier typically relevant to the user and which is unique within the context of the system.

properties.name: period
properties.documentation: Time period during which identifier is/was valid for use.

properties.name: assigner
properties.documentation: Organization that issued/manages the identifier.

properties.name: fhirReference
properties.documentation: A reference from one resource to another.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: reference
properties.documentation: A reference to a location at which the other resource is found. The reference may be a relative reference, in which case it is relative to the service base URL, or an absolute URL that resolves to the location where the resource is found. The reference may be version specific or not. If the reference is not to a FHIR RESTful server, then it should be assumed to be version specific. Internal fragment references (start with '#') refer to contained resources.

properties.name: type
properties.documentation:
The expected type of the target of the reference. If both Reference.type and Reference.reference are populated and Reference.reference is a FHIR URL, both SHALL be consistent.

The type is the Canonical URL of Resource Definition that is the type this reference refers to. References are URLs that are relative to http://hl7.org/fhir/StructureDefinition/ e.g. "Patient" is a reference to http://hl7.org/fhir/StructureDefinition/Patient. Absolute URLs are only allowed for logical models (and can only be used in references in logical models, not resources).

properties.name: identifier
properties.documentation: An identifier for the target resource. This is used when there is no way to reference the other resource directly, either because the entity it represents is not available through a FHIR server, or because there is no way for the author of the resource to convert a known identifier to an actual location. There is no requirement that a Reference.identifier point to something that is actually exposed as a FHIR instance, but it SHALL point to a business concept that would be expected to be exposed as a FHIR instance, and that instance would need to be of a FHIR resource type allowed by the reference.

properties.name: display
properties.documentation: Plain text narrative that identifies the resource in addition to the resource reference.

properties.name: fhirCodeableConcept
properties.documentation: A concept that may be defined by a formal reference to a terminology or ontology or may be provided by text.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: coding
properties.documentation: A reference to a code defined by a terminology system.

properties.name: text
properties.documentation: A human language representation of the concept as seen/selected/uttered by the user who entered the data and/or which represents the intended meaning of the user.

properties.name: fhirPeriod
properties.documentation: A time period defined by a start and end date and optionally time.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: start
properties.documentation: The start of the period. The boundary is inclusive.

properties.name: end
properties.documentation: The end of the period. If the end of the period is missing, it means no end was known or planned at the time the instance was created. The start may be in the past, and the end date in the future, which means that period is expected/planned to end at that time.

properties.name: fhirTiming
properties.documentation: Specifies an event that may occur multiple times. Timing schedules are used to record when things are planned, expected or requested to occur. The most common usage is in dosage instructions for medications. They are also used when planning care of various kinds, and may be used for reporting the schedule to which past regular activities were carried out.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: event
properties.documentation: Identifies specific times when the event occurs.

properties.name: repeat
properties.documentation: A set of rules that describe when the event is scheduled.

properties.name: code
properties.documentation: A code for the timing schedule (or just text in code.text). Some codes such as BID are ubiquitous, but many institutions define their own additional codes. If a code is provided, the code is understood to be a complete statement of whatever is specified in the structured timing data, and either the code or the data may be used to interpret the Timing, with the exception that .repeat.bounds still applies over the code (and is not contained in the code).

properties.name: fhirTiming_Repeat
properties.documentation: Specifies an event that may occur multiple times. Timing schedules are used to record when things are planned, expected or requested to occur. The most common usage is in dosage instructions for medications. They are also used when planning care of various kinds, and may be used for reporting the schedule to which past regular activities were carried out.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: boundsDuration
properties.documentation: Either a duration for the length of the timing schedule, a range of possible length, or outer bounds for start and/or end limits of the timing schedule.

properties.name: boundsRange
properties.documentation: Either a duration for the length of the timing schedule, a range of possible length, or outer bounds for start and/or end limits of the timing schedule.

properties.name: boundsPeriod
properties.documentation: Either a duration for the length of the timing schedule, a range of possible length, or outer bounds for start and/or end limits of the timing schedule.

properties.name: count
properties.documentation: A total count of the desired number of repetitions across the duration of the entire timing specification. If countMax is present, this element indicates the lower bound of the allowed range of count values.

properties.name: countMax
properties.documentation: If present, indicates that the count is a range - so to perform the action between [count] and [countMax] times.

properties.name: duration
properties.documentation: How long this thing happens for when it happens. If durationMax is present, this element indicates the lower bound of the allowed range of the duration.

properties.name: durationMax
properties.documentation: If present, indicates that the duration is a range - so to perform the action between [duration] and [durationMax] time length.

properties.name: durationUnit
properties.documentation: The units of time for the duration, in UCUM units.

properties.name: frequency
properties.documentation: The number of times to repeat the action within the specified period. If frequencyMax is present, this element indicates the lower bound of the allowed range of the frequency.

properties.name: frequencyMax
properties.documentation: If present, indicates that the frequency is a range - so to repeat between [frequency] and [frequencyMax] times within the period or period range.

properties.name: period
properties.documentation: Indicates the duration of time over which repetitions are to occur; e.g. to express "3 times per day", 3 would be the frequency and "1 day" would be the period. If periodMax is present, this element indicates the lower bound of the allowed range of the period length.

properties.name: periodMax
properties.documentation: If present, indicates that the period is a range from [period] to [periodMax], allowing expressing concepts such as "do this once every 3-5 days.

properties.name: periodUnit
properties.documentation: The units of time for the period in UCUM units.

properties.name: dayOfWeek
properties.documentation: If one or more days of week is provided, then the action happens only on the specified day(s).

properties.name: timeOfDay
properties.documentation: Specified time of day for action to take place.

properties.name: when
properties.documentation: An approximate time period during the day, potentially linked to an event of daily living that indicates when the action should occur.

properties.name: offset
properties.documentation: The number of minutes from the event. If the event code does not indicate whether the minutes is before or after the event, then the offset is assumed to be after the event.

properties.name: fhirDuration
properties.documentation: A length of time.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: value
properties.documentation: The value of the measured amount. The value includes an implicit precision in the presentation of the value.

properties.name: comparator
properties.documentation: How the value should be understood and represented - whether the actual value is greater or less than the stated value due to measurement issues; e.g. if the comparator is "<" , then the real value is < stated value.

properties.name: unit
properties.documentation: A human-readable form of the unit.

properties.name: system
properties.documentation: The identification of the system that provides the coded form of the unit.

properties.name: code
properties.documentation: A computer processable form of the unit in some unit representation system.

properties.name: fhirQuantity
properties.documentation: A measured amount (or an amount that can potentially be measured). Note that measured amounts include amounts that are not precisely quantified, including amounts involving arbitrary units and floating currencies.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: value
properties.documentation: The value of the measured amount. The value includes an implicit precision in the presentation of the value.

properties.name: comparator
properties.documentation: How the value should be understood and represented - whether the actual value is greater or less than the stated value due to measurement issues; e.g. if the comparator is "<" , then the real value is < stated value.

properties.name: unit
properties.documentation: A human-readable form of the unit.

properties.name: system
properties.documentation: The identification of the system that provides the coded form of the unit.

properties.name: code
properties.documentation: A computer processable form of the unit in some unit representation system.

properties.name: fhirRange
properties.documentation: A set of ordered Quantities defined by a low and high limit.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: low
properties.documentation: The low limit. The boundary is inclusive.

properties.name: high
properties.documentation: The high limit. The boundary is inclusive.

properties.name: fhirRatio
properties.documentation: A relationship of two Quantity values - expressed as a numerator and a denominator.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: numerator
properties.documentation: The value of the numerator.

properties.name: denominator
properties.documentation: The value of the denominator.

properties.name: fhirSampledData
properties.documentation: A series of measurements taken by a device, with upper and lower limits. There may be more than one dimension in the data.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: origin
properties.documentation: The base quantity that a measured value of zero represents. In addition, this provides the units of the entire measurement series.

properties.name: period
properties.documentation: The length of time between sampling times, measured in milliseconds.

properties.name: factor
properties.documentation: A correction factor that is applied to the sampled data points before they are added to the origin.

properties.name: lowerLimit
properties.documentation: The lower limit of detection of the measured points. This is needed if any of the data points have the value "L" (lower than detection limit).

properties.name: upperLimit
properties.documentation: The upper limit of detection of the measured points. This is needed if any of the data points have the value "U" (higher than detection limit).

properties.name: dimensions
properties.documentation: The number of sample points at each time point. If this value is greater than one, then the dimensions will be interlaced - all the sample points for a point in time will be recorded at once.

properties.name: data
properties.documentation: A series of data points which are decimal values separated by a single space (character u20). The special values "E" (error), "L" (below detection limit) and "U" (above detection limit) can also be used in place of a decimal value.

properties.name: fhirAnnotation
properties.documentation: A  text note which also  contains information about who made the statement and when.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: authorReference
properties.documentation: The individual responsible for making the annotation.

properties.name: authorString
properties.documentation: The individual responsible for making the annotation.

properties.name: time
properties.documentation: Indicates when this particular annotation was made.

properties.name: text
properties.documentation: The text of the annotation in markdown format.

properties.name: fhirObservation_ReferenceRange
properties.documentation: Measurements and simple assertions made about a patient, device or other subject.

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: Unique id for the element within a resource (for internal references). This may be any string value that does not contain spaces.

properties.name: low
properties.documentation: The value of the low bound of the reference range.  The low bound of the reference range endpoint is inclusive of the value (e.g.  reference range is >=5 - <=9). If the low bound is omitted,  it is assumed to be meaningless (e.g. reference range is <=2.3).

properties.name: high
properties.documentation: The value of the high bound of the reference range.  The high bound of the reference range endpoint is inclusive of the value (e.g.  reference range is >=5 - <=9). If the high bound is omitted,  it is assumed to be meaningless (e.g. reference range is >= 2.3).

properties.name: type
properties.documentation: Codes to indicate the what part of the targeted reference population it applies to. For example, the normal or therapeutic range.

properties.name: appliesTo
properties.documentation: Codes to indicate the target population this reference range applies to.  For example, a reference range may be based on the normal population or a particular sex or race.  Multiple `appliesTo`  are interpreted as an "AND" of the target populations.  For example, to represent a target population of African American females, both a code of female and a code for African American would be used.

properties.name: age
properties.documentation: The age at which this reference range is applicable. This is a neonatal age (e.g. number of weeks at term) if the meaning says so.

properties.name: text
properties.documentation: Text based reference range in an observation which may be used when a quantitative range is not appropriate for an observation.  An example would be a reference value of "Negative" or a list or table of "normals".

properties.name: fhirCondition
properties.documentation: A clinical condition, problem, diagnosis, or other event, situation, issue, or clinical concept that has risen to a level of concern.

properties.name: resourceType
properties.documentation: This is a Condition resource

properties.name: id
properties.documentation: The logical id of the resource, as used in the URL for the resource. Once assigned, this value never changes.

properties.name: meta
properties.documentation: The metadata about the resource. This is content that is maintained by the infrastructure. Changes to the content might not always be associated with version changes to the resource.

properties.name: implicitRules
properties.documentation: A reference to a set of rules that were followed when the resource was constructed, and which must be understood when processing the content. Often, this is a reference to an implementation guide that defines the special rules along with other profiles etc.

properties.name: language
properties.documentation: The base language in which the resource is written.

properties.name: text
properties.documentation: A human-readable narrative that contains a summary of the resource and can be used to represent the content of the resource to a human. The narrative need not encode all the structured data, but is required to contain sufficient detail to make it "clinically safe" for a human to just read the narrative. Resource definitions may define what content should be represented in the narrative to ensure clinical safety.

properties.name: contained
properties.documentation: These resources do not have an independent existence apart from the resource that contains them - they cannot be identified independently, and nor can they have their own independent transaction scope.

properties.name: identifier
properties.documentation: Business identifiers assigned to this condition by the performer or other systems which remain constant as the resource is updated and propagates from server to server.

properties.name: clinicalStatus
properties.documentation: The clinical status of the condition.

properties.name: verificationStatus
properties.documentation: The verification status to support the clinical status of the condition.

properties.name: category
properties.documentation: A category assigned to the condition.

properties.name: severity
properties.documentation: A subjective assessment of the severity of the condition as evaluated by the clinician.

properties.name: code
properties.documentation: Identification of the condition, problem or diagnosis.

properties.name: bodySite
properties.documentation: The anatomical location where this condition manifests itself.

properties.name: subject
properties.documentation: Indicates the patient or group who the condition record is associated with.

properties.name: encounter
properties.documentation: The Encounter during which this Condition was created or to which the creation of this record is tightly associated.

properties.name: onsetDateTime
properties.documentation: Estimated or actual date or date-time  the condition began, in the opinion of the clinician.

properties.name: onsetAge
properties.documentation: Estimated or actual date or date-time  the condition began, in the opinion of the clinician.

properties.name: onsetPeriod
properties.documentation: Estimated or actual date or date-time  the condition began, in the opinion of the clinician.

properties.name: onsetRange
properties.documentation: Estimated or actual date or date-time  the condition began, in the opinion of the clinician.

properties.name: onsetString
properties.documentation: Estimated or actual date or date-time  the condition began, in the opinion of the clinician.

properties.name: abatementDateTime

properties.name: fhirMedicationStatement
properties.documentation:
A record of a medication that is being consumed by a patient.   A MedicationStatement may indicate that the patient may be taking the medication now or has taken the medication in the past or will be taking the medication in the future.  The source of this information can be the patient, significant other (such as a family member or spouse), or a clinician.  A common scenario where this information is captured is during the history taking process during a patient visit or stay.   The medication information may come from sources such as the patient's memory, from a prescription bottle,  or from a list of medications the patient, clinician or other party maintains. 

The primary difference between a medication statement and a medication administration is that the medication administration has complete administration information and is based on actual administration information from the person who administered the medication.  A medication statement is often, if not always, less specific.  There is no required date/time when the medication was administered, in fact we only know that a source has reported the patient is taking this medication, where details such as time, quantity, or rate or even medication product may be incomplete or missing or less precise.  As stated earlier, the medication statement information may come from the patient's memory, from a prescription bottle or from a list of medications the patient, clinician or other party maintains.  Medication administration is more formal and is not missing detailed information.

properties.name: Kidney Function
properties.documentation: The ability of the kidney to filter out waste from the bloodstream

properties.name: Urinalysis
properties.documentation: panel of medical tests that includes physical (macroscopic) examination of the urine, chemical evaluation using urine test strips, and microscopic examination.

extensionElements.content: Macroscopic examination targets parameters such as color, clarity, odor, and specific gravity; urine test strips measure chemical properties such as pH, glucose concentration, and protein levels; and microscopy is performed to identify elements such as cells, urinary casts, crystals, and organisms.

properties.name: Kidney Failure
properties.documentation: A condition in which the kidneys lose (part of) their functionality

extensionElements.content: Can be acute or chronic. Irreversible failure requires dialysis or kidney transplant

properties.name: Kidney Transplant
properties.documentation: Transplant of a kidney.

extensionElements.content:
Kidney transplant may be used to treat chronic kidney failure. If an option, has better long term outcomes than dialysis

Kidney transplants do not necessarily require to remove the diseased kidneys

properties.name: Renal Panel Tests
properties.documentation: Renal function tests (or renal panel) are a series of tests that examine how well the kidneys are working in removing waste products (urea, toxins, uric acid) and extra water from the blood (urine) and ensuring proper balance of key chemical elements such as sodium, potassium, calcium

extensionElements.content: Includes Albumin, serum; BUN; BUN:creatinine ratio; calcium, serum; carbon dioxide, total; chloride, serum; creatinine, serum; glucose, serum; phosphorus, serum; potassium, serum; sodium, serum

extensionElements.content: Renal transplantation faces a risk of developing various blood disorders.  Although many etiological factors involve the development of post-transplant blood disorders, immunosuppressive agents, and viral infections could be the two major contributors to most blood disorders and cause hematological abnormalities and immunodeficiency by suppressing hematopoietic function of bone marrow.
A CMP includes all of the components of a Renal Panel except Phosphorus (?)

properties.name: Blood Disorder related to Kidney Transplant

extensionElements.content: The blood disorders typically associated with renal transplantation can be divided into two main categories: (1) Common disorders including post-transplant anemia (PTA), post-transplant lymphoproliferative disorder (PTLD), post-transplant erythrocytosis (PTE), and post-transplant cytopenias (PTC, leukopenia/neutropenia, thrombocytopenia, and pancytopenia); and (2) Uncommon but serious disorders including hemophagocytic syndrome (HPS), thrombotic microangiopathy (TMA), therapy-related myelodysplasia (t-MDS), and therapy-related acute myeloid leukemia (t-AML).
